<section xml:id="sec_sequences_using_dollar_notation">
  <title>Sequences using $ Notation</title>
  <p>
        <idx><h>sequences and series</h><h>$ notation</h></idx>
  </p>
  <p>
    The shortest way to list the terms in a sequence is using the $ symbol.
  </p>
  <p>
    \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {3*k\symbol{94}2+2 $ k=0..3; } \end{mapleinput}
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      The notation for these sequences is
      <me>
        \displaystyle\left(3k^2+2\right)_{k=0}^3
      </me>
      and
      <me>
        \displaystyle\left(2k^2-k\right)_{k=1}^5
      </me>.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <p>
    \relax \begin{maplelatex} {2, 5, 14, 29}{
    <me>
      \displaystyle 2,\,5,\,14,\,29
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    } \end{maplelatex} \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
  <p>
    Now let's generate five integers of the form <m>2k^2-k</m>:
  </p>
  <p>
    \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {2*k\symbol{94}2-k $ k=1..5; } \end{mapleinput} \relax \begin{maplelatex} {1, 6, 15, 28, 45}{
    <me>
      \displaystyle 1,\,6,\,15,\,28,\,45
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    } \end{maplelatex} \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
</section>